<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; MONTANA; SENATOR'S REMARKS SPARK CONTROVERSY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sen. Conrad Burns (R-Mont.), a folksy former radio announcer and livestock 
auctioneer, talked his way into a major campaign controversy when he repeated a 
racial slur and said that living with blacks in Washington "is a hell of a 
challenge." Burns apologized for the comments and defended his record on civil 
rights, but the latest incident that occurred during a visit to the Bozeman 
Daily Chronicle newspaper mushroomed into front-page news across Montana as 
Burns campaigned for a second term in the Senate. Burns has come under fire 
from rights activists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
