<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLSTATE ADMITS POLITICAL CALLS WERE MISLEADING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KENNETH REICH, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Allstate Insurance Co. conceded Friday that some of its employees 
misrepresented themselves as speaking for a police group while soliciting votes 
by telephone for Republican candidate Charles Quackenbush in the insurance 
commissioner's race. 
</P>
<P>
 Delia Chilgren, head of Allstate's California political action group, said 
that fewer than one-third of the company volunteers were given scripts 
instructing them to say they spoke on behalf of the Peace Officers Research 
Assn. of California.She added that many "were uncomfortable" with the 
subterfuge and said instead that they were representing Quackenbush. 
</P>
<P>
 A spokesman for Assemblyman Quackenbush's Democratic opponent, state Sen. Art 
Torres, said the Torres campaign had sent a spy to one of the phone banks, at 
an Allstate office in Monrovia, and had listened as Allstate agents made their 
pitches for Quackenbush by saying they were representatives of the police 
group. 
</P>
<P>
 Chilgren confirmed that one of the phone banks was at the Allstate Monrovia 
office. 
</P>
<P>
 Torres' campaign manager, Dario Frommer, sent a letter to Allstate charging 
the company -- which has a 100% rate increase request for earthquake insurance 
premiums pending in the commissioner's office -- with "perpetrating fraud on 
California voters." 
</P>
<P>
 "It is a crime in California to represent oneself as a peace officer," he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 According to the script, which was obtained by The Times, the Allstate agents 
were instructed to say they were "calling on behalf of" the police group, not 
to say they were police officers. 
</P>
<P>
 The police group has endorsed Quackenbush, but its political director, Kelly 
Moran, said Friday that he has asked Allstate to stop its agents and other 
employees from using the group's name in their calls. 
</P>
<P>
 A spokeswoman for Quackenbush, Lynne Andersen, said the Republican's campaign 
apologizes if any misrepresentations were made and is sending a letter to 
Allstate asking that such misstatements be avoided. 
</P>
</TEXT>
